		{"id":"aes-root-group","type":"group","x":3626,"y":11841,"width":835,"height":567,"label":"The Root"},
		{"id":"aes-definition-group","type":"group","x":3626,"y":12854,"width":835,"height":547,"label":"The Definition"},
		{"id":"pol-bridge-group","type":"group","x":-2091,"y":11841,"width":835,"height":527,"label":"Bridge from Ethics"},
		{"id":"eth-root-group","type":"group","x":413,"y":2826,"width":835,"height":506,"label":"The Root of Value"},
		{"id":"epist-bridge-group","type":"group","x":3520,"y":-8295,"width":807,"height":486,"label":"Bridge from Metaphysics"},
		{"id":"epist-objectivity","type":"text","text":"## Objectivity\n\nVolitional adherence to reality by the method of logic.\n\nConcepts are neither *intrinsic* (existing in the object, independent of any consciousness) nor *subjective* (created by consciousness, independent of reality). They are **objective** — products of a specific relationship between consciousness and existence.\n\nThree positions on universals:\n- **Intrinsicism** — universals exist in reality apart from any mind (Plato)\n- **Subjectivism** — concepts are arbitrary mental constructs (nominalism)\n- **Objectivism** — concepts are a human method of grasping reality, formed by a definite process\n\nTo be objective is to follow a method: reduce every concept and conclusion to its perceptual base, and integrate it with everything else you know. This *is* the method of logic.\n\n*Derives from: Concept Formation — concepts are objective, formed by measurement-omission from real similarities; Reason — objectivity is the method of reason applied to evaluation; Primacy of Existence [metaphysics] — reality is the standard, not consciousness*","x":3883,"y":-4473,"width":723,"height":514,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"epist-emotions","type":"text","text":"## Emotions as Products of Ideas\n\nAn emotion is a **message from the subconscious** about how a fact relates to one's values. It is not always *true*, but it is always a **definite assertion.** Emotions are not tools of cognition — they are automatic responses produced by one's previously held value-judgments and premises (conscious or subconscious). They tell you what your subconscious premises *are*, but cannot tell you whether those premises are *correct.*\n\n**Four primary emotions** and their functions:\n- **Joy** says something has been *gained*. **Sadness** says something has been *lost*. These are the *ends* — the evaluative signals.\n- **Love** (desire in the broadest sense) says something should be *sought*. **Hate** says something should be *avoided*. These are the *means* — the motivational drives toward or away from what will bring joy or sadness.\n\nJoy and sadness make love and hate possible; love and hate drive action toward or away from what will bring joy or sadness. If one did not enjoy sandwiches, one could not desire them; if one did not desire them, one would not walk to the kitchen to make one.\n\n**Complex emotions** have the same function as a primary, only more complex. *Anger*, for instance, is not simple hate (moving away from a threat) but a drive to *deter* threats by inciting retaliation — its content is about injustice, specifically the (false) sense of *intrinsic moral rights*. No such intrinsic rights exist; justice is objective, based on one's relationship to others.\n\nThe error of **emotionalism**: treating emotions as a primary — as a direct pipeline to truth. Emotions are *effects*, valuable as signals from the subconscious, but always requiring conceptual validation before one acts on them. They give you feedback — you can choose whether to go along with them or to think about the situation and go with what makes sense.\n\n*Derives from: Reason — emotions follow from ideas, not vice versa; they are products of prior value-judgments*","x":4717,"y":-4473,"width":668,"height":840,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"epist-arbitrary","type":"text","text":"## The Arbitrary\n\nAn arbitrary claim is one for which there is **no evidence** — neither perceptual nor conceptual. It is not to be regarded as true or false — it is to be *dismissed* as cognitively irrelevant.\n\nThe status of the arbitrary: outside the cognitive realm entirely. The *possible* has some evidence. The *certain* has conclusive evidence. The *arbitrary* has none — it is not a candidate for knowledge.\n\n**The onus of proof:** Whoever asserts must prove. It is not the obligation of others to disprove an unsupported assertion. \"Prove there is no God\" is an illegitimate demand — the burden falls entirely on the one who claims existence.\n\nThe arbitrary includes: floating abstractions with no connection to reality, unfounded \"what if\" scenarios, and claims resting solely on the absence of disproof.\n\n*Derives from: Reason — the arbitrary is excluded from knowledge; reason demands evidence*","x":5496,"y":-4473,"width":668,"height":473,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"epist-man-must-think","type":"text","text":"## Man Must Choose to Think\n\nThe primary volitional act applied to cognition: man must *choose* to engage his rational faculty. Nothing compels a man to think — not instinct, not environment, not society. Thinking is an act of self-generated, self-directed effort.\n\nThis is the bridge between volition and reason. Volition is the metaphysical capacity; the choice to think is its epistemological exercise. A man who does not choose to think has no means of knowing reality.\n\nThe refusal to think — *evasion* — is the root of all evil in the Objectivist framework. Not error (which is innocent), but the willful suspension of consciousness. Error can be corrected; evasion is a moral failure.\n\nFocus is not omniscience — it is the *commitment* to awareness. A man in focus may make mistakes, but he is oriented toward reality. A man in evasion has abandoned that orientation.\n\n*Derives from: Volition — the primary choice is the choice to focus or not*","x":3619,"y":-6295,"width":723,"height":553,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"epist-man-rational-animal","type":"text","text":"## Man: The Rational Animal\n\nMan's distinctive, essential characteristic is his rational faculty. Reason is not one attribute among many — it is the attribute that defines his kind of life and makes all other distinctly human attributes possible.\n\nAn animal adapts to nature through perception and instinct. Man adapts nature to himself through concepts, planning, and production. He survives not by claws or speed but by understanding reality and acting accordingly. No automatic instincts guide him — he must identify the requirements of survival conceptually and *produce* what he needs.\n\nThis is the foundation of ethics: if reason is man's means of survival, then the exercise of reason is his fundamental virtue, and the standard of the good is that which sustains the life of a rational being.\n\n*Derives from: Entity, Identity, Causality [metaphysics] — man is a specific kind of entity whose nature requires reason for survival; Consciousness [metaphysics] — rationality is a form of consciousness*","x":4523,"y":-6295,"width":723,"height":553,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"epist-perceptual-level","type":"text","text":"## The Perceptual Level as the Given\n\n**Sensation** is the irreducible starting point — awareness of a specific quality (a color, a pressure, a sound). **Perception** is the brain's automatic integration of sensations into awareness of *entities* — solid objects with perceivable attributes. No volition, no concepts, no possibility of error at this level.\n\nEntity-perception is **direct** — we perceive entities themselves, not sense-data from which we infer entities. The \"bundle of sensations\" theory (Hume) and representationalism (Locke, Descartes) are both wrong: perception gives us objects, not internal representations that may or may not correspond to reality.\n\nThe perceptual level is the foundation of all higher knowledge. Every concept, principle, and theory must ultimately be reducible to percepts. Animals function at the perceptual level — they know only what is directly before them. Man transcends this through concepts, but never leaves it behind: percepts remain the base.\n\nThe given is not \"subjective\" — it is the automatic, causally necessitated response of a consciousness with identity to the existents it encounters. It is the starting point that makes all knowledge possible.\n\n*Derives from: Validity of the Senses — valid senses produce reliable automatic perceptual integration*","x":2715,"y":-6295,"width":723,"height":553},
		{"id":"epist-measurement-omission","type":"text","text":"## Measurement-Omission\n\nThe specific mechanism that makes concept formation possible — and what makes it a *mathematical* process. When forming a concept, one retains the characteristics but omits their particular measurements, retaining only that measurements *exist* within a certain range.\n\nThe relevant measurements must exist in *some* quantity, but may exist in *any* quantity.\n\nExample: The concept \"table\" retains the characteristics (flat surface, support structure) but omits the specific measurements (2 feet or 4 feet tall, wood or metal). A table must have *some* height — but may have *any* height within the qualifying range.\n\nThis makes concepts *open-ended* — they include all instances, past, present, and future, that share the relevant characteristics regardless of specific measurements. The method is objective because it rests on real, measurable similarities among existents.\n\n*Derives from: Concept Formation — the specific mechanism of the process*","x":2325,"y":-4473,"width":668,"height":514,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"epist-definition","type":"text","text":"## Definition (Essentials)\n\nThe final step of concept-formation: condensing the content of a concept into a brief statement that identifies its units' nature. A proper definition specifies the **genus** (wider class) and **differentia** (what distinguishes these units within that class).\n\nThe *essential* characteristic is the one that explains the greatest number of other distinguishing characteristics. It is not arbitrary — it is determined by the full context of knowledge. As knowledge grows, definitions may be refined (but not invalidated at the level of the essential).\n\nExample: \"Man is the rational animal.\" *Animal* is the genus; *rational* is the differentia — the fundamental characteristic that explains language, technology, art, morality, and all other distinctly human traits.\n\nDefinitions are condensations of enormous cognitive content. They enable **unit-economy**: the mind can hold only so much at once, and definitions make the vast content of concepts manageable.\n\n*Derives from: Concept Formation — definition is the final step, identifying the essential distinguishing characteristic*","x":3104,"y":-4473,"width":668,"height":514,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"aes-sense-of-life","type":"text","text":"## Sense of Life\n\n\"A pre-conceptual equivalent of metaphysics, an emotional, subconsciously integrated appraisal of man and of existence.\" — Rand\n\nFrom early childhood, an individual makes choices and reaches conclusions about concrete problems. These accumulate into an abstract sum — a sense of oneself and the world. A man who characteristically chooses to be mentally active develops a sense of efficacy and optimism; the opposite choice instills helplessness and malevolence.\n\nMost men hardly conceptualize metaphysical issues at all — they remain at the mercy of their inarticulate sense of life. A handful work to translate it into explicit philosophy. Those who succeed bring their conscious and subconscious into harmony; those who default may live tortured by the clash between avowed beliefs and basic feelings.\n\n\"It is the artist's sense of life that controls and integrates his work, directing the innumerable choices he has to make. It is the viewer's or reader's sense of life that responds to a work of art by a complex, yet automatic reaction of acceptance and approval, or rejection and condemnation.\" — Rand\n\nSense-of-life emotions, like all others, are explicable — and alterable, if the facts of reality so demand. Art is inherently philosophical because it must express some sense-of-life emotion, which can be identified and translated into explicit metaphysical value-judgments.\n\n*Derives from: Metaphysical Value-Judgments — sense of life is the subconscious form of MVJs; Emotions as Products of Ideas [epistemology] — sense of life is an emotional integration of metaphysical conclusions*","x":4099,"y":14132,"width":723,"height":646,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"aes-0989c426322aa062","type":"text","text":"## Metaphysical Value-Judgments\n\n\"The link between metaphysics and ethics\" — a category of questions that assumes in man's mind the function of value-judgments with the compelling power of a basic emotion. The fundamental questions: Is the universe intelligible? Can man find happiness? Does man possess the power of choice? Is man to be valued as good or despised as evil?\n\nThese are not ethical questions (\"By what rules should a man live?\") but logically prior ones (\"*Can* man live?\"). Metaphysics thus acts as man's \"value conditioner\" — by specifying what man can realistically aspire to, it tells him how to approach morality.\n\nThe artist, guided by his MVJs (explicit or otherwise), selects from the chaos of human experience those aspects he regards as indicative of the nature of the universe, then embodies them in a perceptual concrete. **Subject** expresses the artist's *metaphysics*; **style** expresses his *psycho-epistemology* — his view of consciousness and its proper method of functioning.\n\nA man's MVJs \"are involved in every moment of his life, in his every choice, decision and action.\" They must be available to him at all times — and available *as a sum.* This is precisely what art makes possible.\n\n*Derives from: Art as Selective Re-Creation — the artist selects according to his metaphysical value-judgments*","x":3264,"y":14132,"width":723,"height":646,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"aes-2b6ac9a9f9b37fa0","type":"text","text":"## Psycho-Epistemological Function of Art\n\n\"Art brings man's concepts to the perceptual level of his consciousness and allows him to grasp them directly, as if they were percepts.\" — Rand\n\nThis is the crux of the Objectivist esthetics. Art completes the chain of unit-economy: percepts → concepts → philosophy → art *returns to percepts*, this time impregnated with abstract meaning. By converting abstractions into percepts, art integrates *and* objectifies metaphysics — making it external, \"out there,\" an existential fact rather than merely a content of consciousness.\n\nThis is an expression of the primacy of existence: consciousness cannot attain fulfillment within its own domain. To satisfy its deepest needs, it must return to its primary task — looking outward. To an entity whose essence is perception, there is no substitute for perception.\n\nTo a rational man, art that objectifies *his* metaphysics provides a unique inspiration — an indispensable source of emotional fuel: \"the life-giving fact of experiencing a moment of *metaphysical* joy — a moment of love for existence.\" Art is \"the technology of the soul\" — what the designer of a bridge is to engineering, the artist is to ethics. Art creates the final product. It builds the model.\n\n*Derives from: Art as Selective Re-Creation — art brings concepts to the perceptual level; Sense of Life — sense of life drives both creation and response; Primacy of Existence [metaphysics] — consciousness must return to perception*","x":3681,"y":15253,"width":723,"height":578,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"eth-honesty","type":"text","text":"## Honesty\n\nThe refusal to fake reality — the recognition that the unreal is unreal and can have no value. Honesty is not primarily a social virtue (\"don't lie to others\") but a metaphysical one: don't attempt to gain values by faking the facts of reality.\n\nThe con man who gains wealth by fraud has not gained a genuine value — he has created a structure built on unreality, which must eventually collapse. He has attempted to make reality other than it is, which is metaphysically impossible.\n\nHonesty includes honesty with oneself — the refusal to evade facts one has perceived, the refusal to pretend that one does not know what one knows. This is why honesty is an aspect of rationality: evasion is the fundamental form of dishonesty.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality — the refusal to fake reality as an aspect of commitment to reason*","x":774,"y":7030,"width":668,"height":496,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"eth-justice","type":"text","text":"## Justice\n\nRationality in the evaluation of men — the practice of judging character and actions objectively, and of granting to each what he has earned. Justice requires both the recognition of virtue and the condemnation of vice.\n\nThe trader principle in human relationships: deal with others by exchanging value for value, by mutual consent. Never seek the unearned — neither in matter nor in spirit. Never grant the undeserved. Judge, and be prepared to be judged.\n\nThe **sanction of the victim**: the moral error of willingly empowering evil by accepting unearned guilt. When good men grant moral legitimacy to those who would destroy them, they become accomplices in their own destruction. Justice demands that one withhold this sanction.\n\nJustice does not mean mercilessness. Forgiveness is proper when someone demonstrates genuine change. But \"mercy\" to evil at the expense of the good — excusing the guilty because punishment is \"harsh\" — is injustice.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality — rationality in evaluating men as an aspect of commitment to reason*","x":1484,"y":7030,"width":668,"height":496,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"eth-productiveness","type":"text","text":"## Productiveness\n\nThe adjustment of nature to man — the process of creating material values by reshaping the natural world to serve human life. Productiveness is the recognition that nature gives nothing for free and that man survives by transforming his environment through the application of reason.\n\nProductiveness requires a **central purpose in life** — a long-range productive goal that integrates and organizes one's lesser goals and daily activities. A man without a central purpose is adrift, regardless of how busy he appears.\n\nWork is not a necessary evil or punishment — it is the fundamental expression of man's nature as a being who survives by thought and production. The spiritual meaning of productive work is that it is the process of shaping one's environment to match one's values — making the world one's own.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality — the adjustment of nature to man as an aspect of commitment to reason*","x":2193,"y":7030,"width":668,"height":496,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"eth-pride","type":"text","text":"## Pride\n\nMoral ambitiousness — the commitment to achieving one's own moral perfection. As productiveness is the shaping of nature to serve man, pride is the shaping of one's own soul to match one's moral ideal.\n\nMoral perfection does not mean infallibility — it means unbreached rationality: the refusal to accept any code of irrational virtues impossible to practice, and the consistent practice of the virtues one knows to be rational. A man of pride does not accept unearned guilt, does not tolerate unexplained defects in his character, and does not give up the effort of moral self-improvement.\n\nPride is the crown of the virtues — the virtue that presupposes and integrates all the others. It is the emotional reward of a life lived in accordance with one's own rational standards: the right to regard oneself as one's highest value.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality — moral ambitiousness as an aspect of commitment to reason*","x":2902,"y":7030,"width":668,"height":496,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"eth-life-qua-rational","type":"text","text":"## Man's Life Qua Rational Being as the Standard\n\nThe standard of value is not mere physical survival at any cost — it is \"man's life *qua* rational being\": the kind of life proper to a being whose means of survival is reason. This distinction is crucial.\n\nA man who \"survives\" by predation, fraud, or parasitism is not living *qua man*. A man who abandons reason and lives moment to moment by range-of-the-moment impulses has abandoned the standard. \"Life qua man\" means: long-range, principled, reason-guided living — the kind of life that includes productive achievement, self-esteem, and the rational enjoyment of values.\n\nMan has a specific nature — and that nature determines the specific form of life that constitutes his good. Man's life is not the life of a dog, or an amoeba, or an angel. It is the life of a rational animal who must think, produce, and choose.\n\n*Derives from: Life as the Standard — specifies the standard for man; Identity [metaphysics] — man has a specific nature; Man: The Rational Animal [epistemology] — man's nature defines the standard*","x":23,"y":5031,"width":723,"height":469,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"eth-values-objective","type":"text","text":"## Values as Objective\n\nValues are neither intrinsic (existing in objects independent of any valuer) nor subjective (created by whims independent of reality). They are **objective**: determined by the relationship between the facts of reality and the requirements of the valuer's life.\n\nThe intrinsicist says: \"This is good because God/Nature/Duty decrees it — regardless of what it does to you.\" The subjectivist says: \"This is good because I feel it/want it — regardless of the facts.\" The objectivist says: \"This is good because it actually sustains my life as a rational being — as identified by reason from the facts.\"\n\nAn objective value is not \"whatever one happens to value\" but \"that which one *ought* to value, given the facts of reality and the requirements of one's life.\" The method of identifying objective values is reason — the same faculty that identifies objective facts.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality — rational evaluation determines objective values; Objectivity [epistemology] — the concept of objectivity applies to values as to all knowledge*","x":913,"y":5031,"width":723,"height":469,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"eth-virtue-practical","type":"text","text":"## Virtue as Practical\n\nThe alleged conflict between the moral and the practical is a false dichotomy produced by the mind-body split. In Objectivist ethics, virtue IS the practical: it is the means by which man sustains his life and achieves his happiness.\n\nThe immoral is the impractical. Evil is metaphysically impotent — it can destroy but cannot create, can parasitize but cannot produce. A man who evades reality may appear to gain in the short term, but his gains are built on unreality and must collapse.\n\n\"The practical man\" who scorns morality and \"the moral man\" who scorns worldly success are two sides of the same counterfeit coin — both accept the premise that virtue requires sacrifice. It does not. Virtue is the *means* to life and happiness, not an obstacle to them.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality — virtue is the means to life, not a sacrifice*","x":-144,"y":8048,"width":723,"height":471,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"eth-harmony-interests","type":"text","text":"## The Harmony of Rational Interests\n\nThere are no conflicts of interest among rational men. Men who pursue rational values by rational means do not clash — they trade to mutual benefit. Conflicts arise only from irrationality: when men seek the unearned, pursue contradictory \"values,\" or resort to force or fraud.\n\nThe alleged \"conflicts\" that supposedly require sacrifice — competition for jobs, resources, romantic partners — are not conflicts among *rational* interests. Two men competing for the same job are not in conflict: the better man earns the position, and the other seeks elsewhere. The conflict model presupposes a zero-sum world, which is the world of the looter, not the trader.\n\nThis principle makes a free society possible. If men's interests necessarily conflicted, social life would require perpetual sacrifice. Because rational interests *harmonize*, a society of free men trading voluntarily is not merely possible but natural.\n\n*Derives from: Justice — just men trade to mutual benefit; Rational Self-Interest — rational egoists do not clash*","x":663,"y":8048,"width":723,"height":471,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"eth-rationality","type":"text","text":"## Rationality: The Cardinal Virtue\n\nIf man's life qua rational being is the standard, and reason is man's sole means of survival, then the fundamental virtue is *rationality*: the recognition and acceptance of reason as one's only source of knowledge, one's only guide to action, and one's only judge of values.\n\nRationality means: full mental focus, a commitment to awareness as a way of life, the refusal to evade any fact. It means: never placing any consideration above reality — not feelings, not wishes, not social pressure, not authority.\n\nAll other virtues — independence, integrity, honesty, justice, productiveness, pride — are aspects and applications of rationality. Rationality is not one virtue among equals; it is the root from which all others grow. A man can fail at any particular virtue only by failing first at rationality — by evading some fact that the virtue requires him to face.\n\n*Derives from: Man's Life Qua Rational Being — life qua man requires reason; The Choice to Live — if you choose to live, reason is the means; Reason [epistemology] — reason is man's means of survival*","x":-422,"y":6013,"width":723,"height":460,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"eth-rational-self-interest","type":"text","text":"## Rational Self-Interest\n\nEach man is the proper beneficiary of his own moral action — he ought to pursue his own life and happiness as his highest purpose. \"Rational\" is the critical qualifier: self-interest means interest as identified by reason, not by whim, impulse, or predation.\n\nThree positions on the beneficiary question: (1) **Altruism** — sacrifice yourself to others; (2) **Predation** — sacrifice others to yourself; (3) **Rational egoism** — pursue your own life by rational means, trading value for value with others. Only the third is consistent with man's nature as a rational being.\n\nThe trader principle follows: deal with others by voluntary exchange, to mutual benefit. Never seek the unearned — neither in matter nor in spirit.\n\n\"I swear by my life and my love of it that I will never live for the sake of another man, nor ask another man to live for mine.\" — Galt's Oath\n\n*Derives from: Rationality — rational pursuit of one's own life; Life Qua Rational Being — each man must sustain his own life by his own effort*","x":413,"y":6013,"width":723,"height":460,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"eth-independence","type":"text","text":"## Independence\n\nOne's acceptance of the responsibility of forming one's own judgments and of living by the work of one's own mind. The independent man is oriented to reality, not to other men — he does not accept ideas on faith, authority, or social pressure.\n\nThe opposite is the \"second-hander\": one who places other people's judgments above his own perception of reality, who lives through others — seeking approval, following the crowd, substituting consensus for cognition.\n\nIndependence does not mean isolation or refusal to learn from others. It means: in any collaboration, one's own rational judgment is the final court of appeal. One can learn from a teacher, but one must understand the lesson — not merely memorize and obey. \"Reason is an attribute of the individual.\" — Peikoff\n\n*Derives from: Rationality — first-hand thinking as an aspect of full commitment to reason*","x":-644,"y":7030,"width":668,"height":496,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"eth-integrity","type":"text","text":"## Integrity\n\nLoyalty to one's rational principles in action — the refusal to permit a breach between one's convictions and one's behavior. Integrity is the recognition that one cannot fake one's own consciousness — that acting against one's knowledge is self-destruction.\n\nThe man of integrity does not sacrifice his convictions to social pressure, economic convenience, or emotional impulse. He recognizes that \"in any compromise between food and poison, it is only death that can win. In any compromise between good and evil, it is only evil that can profit.\"\n\nIntegrity does not mean dogmatic rigidity — if one discovers that one's principles are wrong, reason demands revision. But it means: one does not abandon a principle one knows to be right merely because acting on it is difficult or unpopular.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality — loyalty to rational principles as an aspect of commitment to reason*","x":65,"y":7030,"width":668,"height":496,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"eth-force-evil","type":"text","text":"## The Initiation of Physical Force as Evil\n\nThe initiation of physical force is the practical negation of reason. A man at gunpoint can still think — but he cannot act on his thinking. Since reason is man's means of survival, and force prevents a man from acting on reason, the initiation of force is the fundamental anti-life act.\n\nForce and mind are opposites. Where force rules, reason is impotent; where reason rules, force is unnecessary. The man who resorts to force has abandoned the tool of a rational being — persuasion, trade, voluntary agreement — and substituted the tool of an animal: physical compulsion.\n\nOnly *retaliatory* force — used in response to the initiation of force — is moral. The right of self-defense is the corollary of the right to life. This principle is the bridge from ethics to politics: the sole purpose of a proper government is to protect individual rights by placing retaliatory force under objective control.\n\n*Derives from: Rationality — force negates the mind; The Harmony of Rational Interests — force is the negation of rational interaction*","x":1470,"y":8048,"width":723,"height":471,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"eth-man-end-himself","type":"text","text":"## Man as an End in Himself\n\nEach individual is an end in himself — not a means to the ends of others. This is the ethical corollary of reason being an attribute of the individual: no man can think for another, live for another, or substitute his consciousness for another's.\n\nThe rejection of self-sacrifice does not mean indifference to others. It means that concern for others is a *value* — chosen and earned — not a duty imposed by default. One properly values others in proportion to the values they represent, by the standard of one's own life.\n\nThe opposite view — that man exists to serve others (society, God, the collective) — is the ethics of altruism. It treats man as a sacrificial animal whose purpose is to provide for others' welfare. This is incompatible with man's nature as a rational, volitional being with his own life to sustain.\n\n*Derives from: Rational Self-Interest — the beneficiary question answered*","x":1247,"y":6013,"width":723,"height":460,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"eth-benevolent-universe","type":"text","text":"## The Benevolent Universe Premise\n\nThe universe is not hostile or rigged against man — it is *open* to human achievement. Success, not suffering, is the metaphysically to-be-expected for a rational being. This is not the claim that the universe \"cares\" about man or guarantees success — it means that reality is lawful, knowable, and amenable to rational action.\n\nEvil is metaphysically impotent. It cannot build, create, or produce — it can only destroy and parasitize. Evil can subsist only by leeching from the good: the \"sanction of the victim.\" The good is self-sufficient; evil depends entirely on the good for its continued existence.\n\nMaintaining this premise requires sustained rational effort, and the difficulty varies with one's circumstances. But outside of extreme cases, it is always achievable. Even humor serves to reinforce it: laughter asserts that the irrational is abnormal and should not be taken as the standard of reality.\n\n*Derives from: Virtue as Practical — if virtue is the means to life, the universe is open to the virtuous*","x":2276,"y":8048,"width":723,"height":471,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"epist-volition","type":"text","text":"## Volition: The Epistemological Locus\n\nFree will is a metaphysically given fact (see Metaphysics → \"Volition\"). Its **domain of operation** is epistemological: volition governs the regulation of *awareness*, not primarily of physical action.\n\nThe primary choice: **to focus or not to focus.** This is not a choice among ideas but a choice about whether to *activate* the process of ideation at all. It is irreducible — it cannot be explained by prior ideas, motives, or causes, because grasping any of those requires one to already be in focus.\n\n**The locus of free will is the conscious mind, not the subconscious.** Thoughts arrive unbidden — the subconscious feeds content automatically. But that is not where free will resides. You don't choose what you think specifically, but you choose what to think about broadly, and more fundamentally *whether to focus*. The subconscious is a mechanism — consciousness is the *user* who issues orders, accepts or rejects what comes up, and decides how to file new information.\n\nThree states of consciousness:\n- **Focus** — purposeful alertness, the commitment to full awareness of reality. The *initiation* of the cognitive process. Being unfocused is not being unconscious — there is always a baseline awareness from which one *can* choose to focus.\n- **Drift** — passive, unfocused, letting the mind wander. Not actively destructive, but a default toward cognitive passivity.\n- **Evasion** — the willful suspension of consciousness (Rand). Actively turning away from known facts; placing an \"I wish\" above an \"It is.\" The root of all cognitive failure — not error (which is innocent) but the *refusal* to think.\n\nThis is the **bridge**: volition (metaphysical capacity) → the choice to think (epistemological exercise). Everything in epistemology downstream of this node — reason, logic, concept-formation — depends on a man first choosing to engage his mind. The ability to focus is the essence of what it is to be a human being — it makes man capable of greater heights than any animal, and also of greater depths.\n\n*Derives from: Consciousness [metaphysics] — the metaphysical fact of volition applied to cognition*","x":4523,"y":-7361,"width":723,"height":889,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"epist-logic","type":"text","text":"## Logic\n\nThe art of non-contradictory identification. Logic is the *method* of reason — the *method* of objectivity. It is the volitional application of the law of identity to the process of thought. Its essence: in thinking, one must not contradict oneself, because contradictions cannot exist in reality.\n\nTwo complementary practices:\n- **Reduction** (correspondence) — trace every abstraction back to perceptual reality\n- **Integration** (coherence) — check that every conclusion fits with everything else you know\n\nThese never conflict, because reality coheres.\n\nLogic is not a set of arbitrary formal rules divorced from reality (the rationalist error). Nor is it a social convention (the subjectivist error). It is the method of keeping thought tethered to existence at every step.\n\n*Derives from: Objectivity — logic is the method of objectivity; Reason — logic is the method of reason; Non-Contradiction, Identity [metaphysics] — the epistemological application of A is A*","x":3718,"y":-3466,"width":723,"height":479,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"epist-deduction","type":"text","text":"## Deduction\n\nThe process of applying established general principles to particular cases — drawing conclusions implicit in premises already known. Where induction moves from percepts to principles, deduction moves from principles to their applications.\n\nDeduction is valid only to the extent that its premises are valid — which means they must be hierarchically connected to perceptual evidence. A deductive chain resting on floating abstractions yields no knowledge.\n\nDeduction and induction are complementary, not rival methods. Neither alone suffices. Induction establishes the general principles; deduction applies them to specific cases. Both are forms of logic.\n\nThe **rationalist** error: treating deduction from axioms as the sole method of knowledge, divorced from observation. This yields formal consistency without cognitive content.\n\n*Derives from: Logic — a form of logical inference*","x":4135,"y":-2553,"width":723,"height":457,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"epist-induction","type":"text","text":"## Induction\n\nThe process of reasoning from particular observations to general principles. Based on the law of causality: if entities have identity, their actions flow from their nature — and what is true of an entity's nature is true universally of entities sharing that nature.\n\nInduction is not mere enumeration — not \"I've seen 1000 white swans, so all swans are white.\" Proper induction identifies the *causal* basis: *why* the observed regularity holds, rooted in the identity of the entities involved.\n\nContextual certainty is achievable: when you have identified the causal factor and found no evidence of countervailing factors within your context, you are entitled to generalize — with certainty, *within that context.*\n\nThe number of observations needed depends not on some fixed threshold, but on whether the causal mechanism has been isolated.\n\n*Derives from: Logic — a form of logical inference; Causality, Identity [metaphysics] — entities act according to their nature*","x":3162,"y":-2553,"width":723,"height":457,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"epist-consciousness-identity","type":"text","text":"## Consciousness as Possessing Identity\n\nConsciousness, like every other existent, has identity — a specific nature that determines *how* it perceives. The senses have a definite form: they respond to specific stimuli in specific ways. This is not a defect — it is a precondition of awareness.\n\nThe **form-object distinction** (traceable to Aquinas): there is the thing you are aware of (the object), and the form in which you are aware of it. Your form of awareness is not a barrier between you and reality — it *is* your mode of contact with reality.\n\nA color-blind man and a normal-sighted man perceive the same object in different forms — neither is wrong. Differences in sensory form have no cognitive consequences: beings with radically different senses would reach the same scientific conclusions about the same reality.\n\n*Derives from: Identity (A is A) [metaphysics] — identity applies to consciousness as to everything else*","x":3562,"y":-8251,"width":723,"height":402},
		{"id":"epist-senses-valid","type":"text","text":"## The Sensory-Perceptual Base\n\nThe validity of the senses is a metaphysical corollary (see Metaphysics → \"Validity of the Senses\"). Its epistemological significance: the senses provide the **irreducible starting material** for all knowledge.\n\nThe senses give evidence of *existence* — they tell us that something *is*. But *what* it is must be identified by reason. \"The task of man's senses is to give him the evidence of existence, but the task of identifying it belongs to his reason.\" — Rand\n\nError arises only at the **conceptual** level, never in the sensory data itself. A boy sees a man in a red suit and infers Santa Claus — his senses made no error; his conclusion did. A stick appears bent in water — the senses faithfully report the full physical context (including refraction). The data is always reliable; the *interpretation* may not be.\n\nThe **given** (perception) vs. the **interpreted** (concepts): perception is the unchallengeable starting point. You may question any concept, theory, or principle — but you cannot challenge the perceptual data without using perceptual data to do so. The given is epistemologically foundational.\n\nConsequence: every concept and principle must be **traceable to perceptual evidence.** Claims that cannot be so traced are *floating abstractions* — severed from reality, cognitively void. This is the deepest root of the Objectivist demand for reduction.\n\n*Derives from: Validity of the Senses [metaphysics]; Consciousness as Possessing Identity*","x":2896,"y":-7361,"width":723,"height":610},
		{"id":"epist-concept-formation","type":"text","text":"## Concept Formation\n\nThe fundamental process of human knowledge: **mental integration by measurement-omission.** Man observes particular entities (percepts), isolates groups by similarity, and unites them into a single mental unit — a concept — by retaining their common characteristics while omitting particular measurements.\n\nThe process: (1) **Differentiation** — isolating a group of existents from all others on the basis of observed differences; (2) **Integration** — uniting them on the basis of observed similarities. What makes this non-arbitrary is the **Conceptual Common Denominator (CCD)**: a characteristic reducible to a unit of measurement, possessed by the units being integrated *and* by the existents from which they are being differentiated — but differing in specific measurement. One can only compare existents that are commensurable — that share a CCD.\n\nNeither nominalism (concepts are arbitrary labels) nor realism (concepts refer to transcendent Forms). Concepts are **objective** — grounded in real, measurable similarities, formed by a definite method. This is the answer to the \"problem of universals\" that plagued philosophy since the Greeks.\n\n*Derives from: The Perceptual Level as the Given — concepts are formed from percepts*","x":2993,"y":-5459,"width":723,"height":486,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"epist-reason","type":"text","text":"## Reason\n\nThe faculty that identifies and integrates the material provided by man's senses. Three essential elements: its data (percepts), its form (concepts), its method (logic). Reason is man's *only* means of knowledge.\n\nIs reason valid? The question reduces to: are the senses valid? are concepts valid? is logic valid? Yes on all counts. Reason is the existence-oriented faculty — it begins with facts, organizes them in accordance with facts, and is guided at every step by rules resting on the law of identity.\n\n**Against mysticism:** No \"revelation,\" \"intuition,\" or \"faith\" can substitute for reason. There is no non-sensory, non-rational faculty of knowledge.\n\n**Against skepticism:** The skeptic claims reason is impotent — but this claim is itself a product of reasoning, and is therefore self-refuting.\n\n*Derives from: Man Must Choose to Think — reason is volitional, must be activated by choice; Man: The Rational Animal — reason is man's basic means of survival*","x":4105,"y":-5459,"width":723,"height":486,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"epist-hierarchy","type":"text","text":"## Hierarchy of Knowledge\n\nHuman knowledge is not a collection of isolated propositions — it is a hierarchical structure, built layer upon layer from a perceptual base. Every concept, principle, and theory depends on prior concepts and principles, ultimately reducible to percepts.\n\n**Reduction** is the process of tracing a cognitive item back through the hierarchy to its perceptual base. Any claim that cannot be reduced — that \"floats\" without hierarchical support — is cognitively void.\n\nThe concept \"justice\" depends on \"rights,\" which depends on \"man's nature,\" which depends on \"life,\" which depends on percepts of living organisms. Break any link and the higher concept becomes a floating abstraction.\n\nThe hierarchy runs: percepts → first-level concepts → higher abstractions → principles → complex theories. Each level depends on those below. Reversing the hierarchy (deducing percepts from abstractions) is the error of rationalism.\n\n*Derives from: Reason — knowledge must be reduced to perceptual evidence; Induction — inductive generalizations build the hierarchy; Deduction — deduction applies hierarchical principles to particulars*","x":3579,"y":-1893,"width":723,"height":513,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"epist-certainty","type":"text","text":"## Certainty as Contextual\n\nKnowledge can be certain — within a context. Certainty does not require omniscience. It requires that a conclusion be established by the full context of available evidence, with no contradictory evidence and no unresolved rational doubts.\n\nContextual certainty is the only kind of certainty possible to a human consciousness.\n\nThe **fallibilist** says: you might be wrong, so you can never be certain. The **infallibilist** says: certainty requires absolute, final proof. Both are wrong. Certainty is an *epistemological* status — established beyond rational doubt within the current context of knowledge.\n\nNew evidence may require revision — but this does not retroactively invalidate prior certainty. The demand for non-contextual certainty is the demand for omniscience — an attack on human knowledge as such.\n\n*Derives from: Hierarchy of Knowledge — certainty is contextual and hierarchical, depending on the chain of evidence back to perception*","x":3579,"y":-1164,"width":723,"height":451,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"eth-fundamental-alternative","type":"text","text":"## The Fundamental Alternative: Existence or Non-Existence\n\nOnly living organisms face the alternative of existence or non-existence — and this is what makes the concept of \"value\" possible. A rock cannot go out of existence *qua rock*; it merely changes form. But a living organism must continually act to sustain its own life — or perish.\n\nLife is a process of self-sustaining and self-generated action. An organism that fails to act in accordance with its nature ceases to exist as a living organism. This is the fundamental alternative that gives rise to all goals, all values, all purposes.\n\nThe \"immortal robot\" argument: a being that could not be destroyed, that faced no alternative of existence or nonexistence, would have no values — nothing to gain or lose. It is only because life is *conditional* — because living organisms can fail — that the concept \"value\" has any meaning.\n\n\"It is only the concept of 'Life' that makes the concept of 'Value' possible.\" — Rand\n\n*Derives from: Existence Exists [metaphysics], Entity [metaphysics], Causality [metaphysics] — living entities are goal-directed because they face the alternative*","x":468,"y":2847,"width":723,"height":466},
		{"id":"eth-life-standard","type":"text","text":"## Life as the Standard of Value\n\nLife is not merely what makes values possible — it is the standard by which they are measured. \"Value\" is that which one acts to gain and/or keep; the ultimate value, the final goal that sets the standard for all lesser goals, is the organism's own life.\n\nThe good is that which promotes the organism's life; the evil is that which threatens or destroys it. This is not a moral commandment but a metaphysical identification of the relationship between living organisms and values.\n\nThe standard is not a \"desire to live\" (one could desire anything); it is the objective requirements of life itself — the factual conditions an organism's nature demands for its survival. Ethics is thus grounded in biology: the nature of a living organism determines what is good or evil *for it.*\n\n*Derives from: The Fundamental Alternative — life-or-death is what makes values possible and necessary; Causality [metaphysics] — living entities act to sustain themselves*","x":23,"y":3981,"width":723,"height":434},
		{"id":"eth-choice-to-live","type":"text","text":"## The Choice to Live\n\nMan, unlike plants and animals, has no automatic code of values — he must choose them, starting with the most fundamental: the choice to live. This choice is pre-moral: it cannot itself be proved or derived from ethics, because it is the precondition of all valuation.\n\nThe choice is implicit in every purposeful action. Every time a man sets a goal, takes a step, or makes a plan, he is operationally committed to his own life — whether he acknowledges it or not.\n\nGiven this choice, ethics becomes absolute. The structure is: *if* you choose to live, *then* a specific, objective code of values follows. The \"if\" is not arbitrary — it is the foundation that makes the \"then\" possible. One is free to reject life — but not free to reject life and expect to flourish.\n\n*Derives from: Life as the Standard — the standard gives the choice its content; Volition [epistemology] — the choice is volitional, not automatic*","x":913,"y":3981,"width":723,"height":434,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"eth-right-to-property","type":"text","text":"## Right to Property (Ethical Root)\n\nIf man must produce to live, and production requires the exercise of reason applied to nature, then man must have the right to keep, use, and dispose of the product of his effort. Without property rights, productiveness is rendered futile — the incentive to create is destroyed when the product can be seized.\n\nProperty is not a social convention but a moral requirement rooted in man's nature. The right to property is the right to the *action* of producing and to the *result* of that action. It is the implementation of the right to life in the material sphere.\n\nThis is the ethical root — the political elaboration (how property rights are defined, adjudicated, and protected by government) belongs to the politics canvas. The bridge: the initiation of force as evil implies that no one may seize another's product by force.\n\n*Derives from: Productiveness — if you must produce, you must keep the product; Man as an End in Himself — man's right to the product of his effort; The Initiation of Force as Evil — property rights protect against force*","x":954,"y":8985,"width":723,"height":462,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"eth-happiness","type":"text","text":"## Happiness as the Moral Purpose\n\nHappiness is \"a state of noncontradictory joy — a joy without penalty or guilt, a joy that does not clash with any of one's values and does not work for one's own destruction.\" It is the emotional state that results from the achievement of one's rational values.\n\nHappiness is not the *standard* of value — that is man's life. It is the *purpose*: the emotional reward of living morally. The distinction matters: using happiness as the standard leads to hedonism (whatever feels good is good); using life as the standard and happiness as the purpose means that genuine happiness follows only from rational values.\n\nThe moral-practical unity means that happiness is the *normal condition* of a rational man — not a miraculous exception but the natural consequence of living in accordance with reality. Because the universe is open to man's achievement, happiness is the metaphysically to-be-expected for those who live rationally.\n\n*Derives from: The Benevolent Universe Premise — success is the metaphysically normal; Rational Self-Interest — happiness is the purpose of moral action; Emotions as Products of Ideas [epistemology] — happiness is an emotional state following from values*","x":120,"y":8985,"width":723,"height":462,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"pol-6ca80daaebefbead","type":"text","text":"## From Ethics to Politics: The Bridge\n\nMan as an end in himself is an ethical principle (see Ethics). Its political significance: an individual living alone needs only ethics — but among other men, he needs a principle that *protects* his moral sovereignty in a social context.\n\nEthics says: each man ought to live by his own rational judgment. But in society, other men can negate that judgment by force. The question becomes: what social conditions does man's nature require? The answer is the concept that provides \"the logical transition from the principles guiding an individual's actions to the principles guiding his relationship with others\" — *individual rights.*\n\nThis is why politics is a branch of ethics, not an independent discipline. Every political principle — rights, government, capitalism — is derived from the ethical fact that man is an end in himself and must be free to act on his own judgment.\n\n*From: Man as an End in Himself [ethics], Rational Self-Interest [ethics]*","x":-2035,"y":11910,"width":723,"height":417},
		{"id":"pol-880f7d490ef248b1","type":"text","text":"## Individual Rights\n\n\"Rights are a moral concept — the concept that provides a logical transition from the principles guiding an individual's actions to the principles guiding his relationship with others — the concept that preserves and protects individual morality in a social context.\" — Rand\n\n**The hierarchy of rights:**\n- **Right to Life** (fundamental) — the source of all rights\n- **Right to Liberty** — freedom to act on one's own judgment\n- **Right to Property** — the right to the product of one's effort\n- **Right to the Pursuit of Happiness** — the right to live for one's own sake\n\nRights are *negative*: freedom FROM coercion, not claims ON others' effort. There are no \"rights\" to the labor of other men. Rights are *absolute*: they cannot be morally infringed for any reason — not \"the public good,\" not majority vote, not \"social justice.\" Rights are *inalienable*: even when violated by criminals, the right remains on the side of the victim.\n\n**Rand's crucial discovery:** rights can be violated by one means only — the initiation of physical force (including indirect forms such as fraud).\n\n*From: Man as End in Himself [ethics], Justice [ethics], Right to Property [ethics]*","x":-2035,"y":12773,"width":723,"height":547,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"pol-a828fe67117c2eeb","type":"text","text":"## The Non-Initiation of Force Principle\n\n\"The rights of man can be violated by one means only: by the initiation of physical force. One cannot expropriate a man's values, or prevent him from pursuing values, or enslave him in any manner at all, except by the use of physical force.\" — Peikoff\n\nForce is the *only* action that negates the victim's mind — the only act that literally stops human self-preservation. Since reason is man's means of survival, and force prevents a man from acting on reason, the initiation of force is the fundamental anti-life act in a social context.\n\nOnly *retaliatory* force — used in response to initiation — is moral. The right of self-defense is the corollary of the right to life. All human relationships must be voluntary: persuasion, trade, agreement — never compulsion.\n\nThis is the ethical principle (force as evil) translated into the political principle: government exists to ban initiation and to place retaliatory force under objective control.\n\n*From: Individual Rights + Initiation of Force as Evil [ethics]*","x":-2453,"y":13814,"width":723,"height":438,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"pol-30d862a9102eed63","type":"text","text":"## The Trader Principle\n\nValue for value. Voluntary exchange to mutual benefit. No sacrifice of self to others; no sacrifice of others to self. The trader principle is the only rational form of human interaction — men deal with one another by exchanging value for value, by mutual consent.\n\nThe ethical root is rational self-interest: a rational man does not seek the unearned, neither in matter nor in spirit. He does not sacrifice his values to others or demand that others sacrifice to him. He trades — creating value and exchanging it freely.\n\nUnder capitalism, the trader principle becomes the economic principle: the free market is the trader principle writ large — voluntary exchange of goods, services, and ideas without government interference. Capitalism is the system that makes the trader principle possible by banning the only alternative to trade: physical force.\n\n*From: Individual Rights + Rational Self-Interest [ethics] + Harmony of Interests [ethics]*","x":-1618,"y":13814,"width":723,"height":438,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"pol-b8340f2fd36c0ef6","type":"text","text":"## Limited Government\n\n\"A government is an institution that holds the exclusive power to enforce certain rules of social conduct in a given geographical area.\" — Rand\n\nIn a proper society, the government is the *servant* of the citizens, not their ruler. It is the agent of man's self-defense — and an agent may not initiate force against the innocent. Government has a single delegated power: to use force in *retaliation only*, against those who start its use.\n\n**Three and only three functions:**\n1. **The police** — to protect men from criminals\n2. **The armed services** — to protect men from foreign invaders\n3. **The law courts** — to settle disputes according to objective laws\n\nAny additional function requires the government to *initiate* force against innocent citizens — at which point it becomes a criminal, not a protector. \"Government is inherently negative. The power of force is the power of destruction, not of creation, and it must be used accordingly — only to destroy destruction.\"\n\nBy its nature, government holds a monopoly on the use of force. Citizens delegate their right of self-defense to prevent gang warfare and mob rule.\n\n*From: Individual Rights + Non-Initiation of Force*","x":-2453,"y":15071,"width":723,"height":578,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"pol-objective-law","type":"text","text":"## Objective Law\n\n\"A government is the means of placing the retaliatory use of physical force under *objective control* — i.e., under objectively defined laws.\" — Peikoff\n\nA proper government is a \"government of laws, not of men.\" Objective law has two essential features:\n\n**1. Objective validation:** Laws must be rationally grounded in the protection of individual rights. The only system of laws that excludes every element of the nonobjective is one that confines legislation to the protection of rights.\n\n**2. Objective interpretation:** Rational laws prohibit only crimes defined in terms of *specific physical acts*. A citizen can know, before acting, whether the law forbids it — the meaning is grasped from the statement of the law itself. This stands in stark contrast to nonobjective laws forbidding \"blasphemy,\" \"obscenity,\" \"unfair profits,\" or \"restraint of trade\" — where men must guess at the legislator's intentions.\n\n**Nonobjective law** is the negation of government's purpose: \"a monopoly on the use of force granted to an agency ruled by whim — a government of men and not of laws — a formal authorization for the state to swallow up the citizens.\"\n\n*From: Limited Government — government acts under objective control*","x":-1618,"y":15071,"width":723,"height":578,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"pol-84c75b9c48f22a02","type":"text","text":"## Laissez-Faire Capitalism\n\n\"Capitalism is a social system based on the recognition of individual rights, including property rights, in which all property is privately owned.\" — Rand\n\nUnder capitalism, state and economics are separated just as state and church are — and for the same reason: the mind requires freedom. Producers obey the criminal law and abide by court decisions, but otherwise the government's policy is: *hands off.*\n\n**The only moral social system.** \"Since rights are the means of subordinating society to moral law, capitalism is the only moral social system.\" It is the only system that bans force from human relationships and makes the achievement of virtue possible.\n\n**The system of objectivity.** \"Capitalism implements the right code of morality because it is based on the right view of metaphysics and epistemology. It is the system of virtue because it is the system of objectivity.\" Capitalism protects objective rights by means of objective laws — allowing cause and effect to operate unimpeded.\n\nWhat capitalism guarantees is that if a man chooses to think, he *can* act accordingly. No one has the power to neutralize the mind.\n\n*From: Individual Rights + Trader Principle + Non-Initiation of Force + Limited Government + Objective Law*","x":-2035,"y":16297,"width":723,"height":547,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"pol-statism","type":"text","text":"## Statism: The Politics of Unreason\n\n\"Statism\" means any system that concentrates power in the state at the expense of individual freedom. It subsumes theocracy, absolute monarchy, Nazism, fascism, communism, democratic socialism, and dictatorship. The variants differ on form, tactics, and ideology — but the essence is the same: \"war against man — against his mind, body, and property alike.\"\n\n**\"Just as individualism is the politics demanded by reason, so statism is the politics of unreason.\"** A free system flows from a philosophy that accepts reality, reason, egoism, and productiveness. An unfree system flows from and fosters the opposite.\n\n**Anarchism** is not the opposite of statism — it is a variant of it. \"The only referent of 'anarchism' — the only possible political system it designates — is some variant of statism.\" Without government, men resort to gang warfare; the result is the negation, not the extreme, of freedom.\n\n**The mixed economy** is \"not a 'third way' between capitalism and socialism. It is merely a transition stage, a disintegrating antisystem, careening drunkenly but inexorably from freedom to dictatorship.\" It rests on pragmatism and eclecticism — the attempt to combine essentials from contradictory approaches.\n\n*Negated by: Individual Rights, Objective Law, Laissez-Faire Capitalism*","x":-2035,"y":17270,"width":723,"height":547,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"aes-32c85169e9a25f2c","type":"text","text":"## Man's Need for Art\n\nArt is a need of the mind — of man *qua* thinker and valuer. A conceptual consciousness requires the ultimate integration of its contents that only philosophy can provide: a view of existence as a whole. But philosophical principles are the widest of all abstractions — no one can hold such complexity in focus *as a sum.*\n\nThe chain of unit-economy: percepts are condensed into concepts; concepts are condensed into philosophy; and art condenses philosophy — by returning to the perceptual level, this time in a form impregnated with profound abstract meaning. Art gives man a concrete on which he can choose to focus, carrying with it the meaning of his whole view of life.\n\n\"Art is inextricably tied to man's survival — not to his physical survival, but to that on which his physical survival depends: to the preservation and survival of his consciousness.\" — Rand\n\nThis is why art has always existed among men, from prehistory to the present, and why animals have neither art nor any equivalent of it.\n\n*Derives from: Concept Formation [epistemology] — conceptual beings need to experience abstractions as concretes; Man: The Rational Animal [epistemology] — man's conceptual nature creates the need for art*","x":3681,"y":11881,"width":723,"height":506},
		{"id":"aes-db225a92638bd5ea","type":"text","text":"## Art: Selective Re-Creation of Reality\n\n\"Art is a selective re-creation of reality according to an artist's metaphysical value-judgments.\" — Rand\n\nThe operative word is *selective.* Art is not reproduction, journalism, or photography. The artist does not report neutrally on \"the way things are\" — he re-creates reality from his own metaphysical perspective. He isolates what he regards as essential and integrates it into a new concrete that represents an embodied abstraction.\n\nAn art work tells man not that something *is*, but that it is *important.* \"Important\" is the esthetic criterion — distinct from the epistemological \"essential\" and the ethical \"good.\" Everything included in a work of art acquires metaphysical significance by the mere fact of being included. A cold sore on a painted goddess is not a medical fact — it is a metaphysical statement.\n\nThe role of art is not didactic. \"The basic purpose of art is *not* to teach, but to *show* — to hold up to man a concretized image of his nature and his place in the universe.\" — Rand. In life, one ignores the unimportant; in art, one omits it.\n\n*Derives from: Man's Need for Art — the need determines the nature of art*","x":3681,"y":12894,"width":723,"height":486,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"aes-romanticism","type":"text","text":"## Romanticism\n\n\"A category of art based on the recognition of the principle that man possesses the faculty of volition.\" — Rand\n\nThe Romantic school arose on the heels of the Enlightenment, when an Aristotelian sense of life dominated the culture — a subconscious confidence in man's mind, with capitalism as its political corollary. What united the Romanticists was the principle that man is self-directed and goal-directed; what they rejected was determinism.\n\n**Plot** is the literary expression of purposeful action: \"a purposeful progression of logically connected events leading to the resolution of a climax.\" Plot implies that *life* is logical — a man's choices shape his fate. **Characterization** is abstract projection: characters are \"larger than life,\" presenting essential human attributes in purer form — embodied universals, not reproductions of concretes.\n\n**Naturalism** is the opposite: determinism, plotlessness, statistics as the standard. By substituting \"what happens to happen\" for \"what counts about man,\" Naturalism negates art's essential function.\n\n**Romantic Realism** is Rand's synthesis: \"I am Romantic in the sense that I present men as they ought to be. I am Realistic in the sense that I place them here and now and on this earth.\" Romanticism is \"objectively the greatest achievement in art history.\"\n\n*Derives from: Volition [epistemology] — Romanticism is art based on recognition of volition; Metaphysical Value-Judgments — Romanticism affirms volition as metaphysically significant; Sense of Life — an Aristotelian sense of life gave rise to Romanticism*","x":3681,"y":16318,"width":723,"height":648,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"aes-humor","type":"text","text":"## Humor\n\n\"Humor is the denial of metaphysical significance to that which you laugh at.\" — Rand\n\nWhen you laugh at something, you declare it unreal, abnormal, insignificant. Humor is inherently destructive — and this is appropriate, provided it is aimed at what deserves destruction: evil, irrationality, and vice. To mock virtue is vicious; to mock vice is healthy.\n\nHumor reinforces the benevolent universe premise. By laughing at the irrational, one asserts that it is the exception, the abnormal — not the standard of reality. Comedy provides fuel by presenting the vicious in its proper light.\n\nWhat one finds funny reflects one's sense of life. A man with genuine values will not find funny a joke that mocks what he truly values, regardless of how cleverly it is constructed. \"If it's funny, it's funny\" is pseudo-objectivity — a refusal to recognize that comedy necessarily carries moral implications.\n\nAnti-rational humor — humor that requires suppressing logic to find amusing — is contemptible. Not all evil is appropriate material for comedy: actual manifestations of evil must be taken seriously, but the *potency* or *necessity* of evil need not be.\n\n*Derives from: Metaphysical Value-Judgments — humor is the denial of metaphysical significance; Sense of Life — what you find funny reflects your implicit metaphysics; Benevolent Universe Premise [ethics] — humor reinforces the benevolent universe premise*","x":4460,"y":16318,"width":723,"height":648,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"aes-esthetic-objective","type":"text","text":"## Esthetic Value as Objective\n\nEsthetic value is neither \"in the object\" (intrinsicism) nor \"in the eye of the beholder\" (subjectivism). Beauty is *objective*: \"in the object — as judged by a rational beholder.\" Three esthetic principles define the standard:\n\n**1. Selectivity in regard to subject** — \"the primary, the essential, the cardinal aspect of art.\" The artist must make a conscious, rational choice of subject given his sense of life. No random, second-handed, or metaphysically meaningless subjects. Art devoid of meaning is devoid of esthetic value.\n\n**2. Clarity** — Art must be \"fully intelligible.\" The artist's function is to overcome the opacity of experience and reveal essence through judicious selectivity. Art must conform to the requirements of man's cognitive faculty — the rules identified by epistemology are not malleable to anyone's desires.\n\n**3. Integration** — \"The hallmark of art.\" Nothing accidental. Every item must be weighed against the theme and presented as an attribute of an indivisible whole. Anything insignificant destroys the spell — the integrity and power of the stylization. \"Nothing in this film is accidental\" — the motto of great art.\n\n**Nonobjective art** is to art what the arbitrary is to cognition: *anti-art.* It is the attempt not to re-create but to annihilate reality, not to integrate but to disintegrate consciousness.\n\n*Derives from: Art as Selective Re-Creation — selectivity is the cardinal principle; Psycho-Epistemological Function — art must conform to cognitive requirements; Objectivity [epistemology] — the method of objectivity applies to esthetic judgment; Values as Objective [ethics] — esthetic value is objective, like moral value*","x":3681,"y":17351,"width":723,"height":668,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"legend-grey","type":"text","text":"**Corollaries**","x":-1448,"y":-10254,"width":501,"height":105},
		{"id":"legend-1","type":"text","text":"**Axioms**","x":-1448,"y":-10113,"width":501,"height":105,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"legend-2","type":"text","text":"**Volitional**","x":-1448,"y":-9973,"width":501,"height":105,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"legend-3","type":"text","text":"**Corrective / Contrast**","x":-1448,"y":-9833,"width":501,"height":105,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"legend-4","type":"text","text":"**Virtues / Applications**","x":-1448,"y":-9692,"width":501,"height":105,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"legend-6","type":"text","text":"**Integration / Culmination**","x":-1448,"y":-9411,"width":501,"height":105,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"legend-5","type":"text","text":"**Reason / Method**","x":-1448,"y":-9553,"width":501,"height":105,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"meta-existence","type":"text","text":"## Existence Exists\n\nThe irreducible starting point: *there is something rather than nothing.* \"Existence\" is the widest of all concepts — it subsumes every entity, action, attribute, and relationship.\n\nThis axiom cannot be proved — proof presupposes it. It is validated **ostensively**: by pointing to reality. Any act of perception already contains it. To deny it is to use it — the denier must exist to make the denial, must use concepts that refer to existents, must presuppose a world in which denial is possible.\n\n\"We start as philosophers where we began as babies, at the only place there is to begin: by looking at the world.\" — Peikoff, OPAR\n\nRand: *\"Existence exists — and the act of grasping that statement implies two corollary axioms: that something exists which one perceives and that one exists possessing consciousness.\"*\n\n**Status:** Axiom (perceptual self-evidency, implicit from the first sensation)\n**Validation:** Ostensive — look at reality\n**Denial is self-refuting:** To say \"nothing exists\" is to assert something, from somewhere, using concepts — all of which presuppose existence","x":-3854,"y":-8156,"width":695,"height":590,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"meta-consciousness","type":"text","text":"## Consciousness Exists\n\nYou are aware — and awareness is always awareness *of something.* Consciousness is \"the faculty of perceiving that which exists.\" It is not inherent in existence as such (a world without conscious organisms is possible), but it is inherent in your *grasp* of existence.\n\n\"There is something — *of which I am aware*.\" This recognition is implicit in every act of cognition.\n\nA consciousness with nothing to be conscious of is a contradiction. A consciousness conscious of nothing but itself is a contradiction — \"before it could identify itself as consciousness, it had to be conscious of something.\" — Rand\n\nAgainst Descartes: \"I think therefore I am\" is true, but taking it as the starting point implies you must infer existence from consciousness. In metaphysical fact, existence comes first — you cannot be aware before something exists. Existence and consciousness are grasped simultaneously, but existence has metaphysical priority.\n\n**Status:** Axiom (implicit once the child differentiates inner from outer world)\n**Validation:** Ostensive — the fact that you are perceiving\n**Denial is self-refuting:** To deny consciousness is to exercise it","x":-3047,"y":-8156,"width":695,"height":590,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"meta-identity","type":"text","text":"## A is A (The Law of Identity)\n\nTo be is to be *something* — to have a nature, to possess identity. A thing is itself. Every existent has specific attributes and no others.\n\nRand's formulation: **\"Existence is identity.\"** Not \"existence *has* identity\" — which would suggest identity is separable from existence, like paint from a house. To be *is* to be something. Existence and identity are indivisible.\n\n\"Existence\" differentiates a thing from nothing (it *is* vs. it *is not*). \"Identity\" differentiates one thing from another (it is *this* vs. it is *that*). Two perspectives on the same indivisible fact.\n\nThe law of identity is the foundation of all logic, all science, all inferential knowledge. \"You couldn't do logic if you didn't have the rule of non-contradiction. If you didn't care about non-contradiction, any series of steps whatsoever would be valid — but they wouldn't correspond to reality.\" — Tew\n\nFirst explicitly identified by Antonius Andreas (medieval), though implicit in everything Aristotle does.\n\n**Status:** Axiom (implicit once the child differentiates *this* object from *that*)\n**Validation:** Ostensive — everything you perceive is something specific\n**Denial is self-refuting:** To deny identity is to assert that the denial is *something* — a specific claim with a specific meaning","x":-2241,"y":-8156,"width":695,"height":590,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"meta-permanence","type":"text","text":"## Material Permanence\n\nIf existence exists, then entities cannot be created from nothing or annihilated into nothing. They may change attributes, split, merge, transform — but cannot come from or become *nonexistence.* \"Nothing does not exist\" is a core Objectivist premise.\n\n\"'Creation' does not (and metaphysically cannot) mean the power to bring something into existence out of nothing. 'Creation' means the power to bring into existence an arrangement of natural elements that had not existed before.\" — Rand\n\nThe universe is a **plenum** — solidly packed, no void, no empty space. \"There is no such thing as nothing. The universe is all there is. There's nothing outside the universe. There are no gaps inside the universe.\" — Tew (tracing to Parmenides)\n\nSpace is not a container into which things are placed — it is a **relational concept** among things (Aristotelian vs. Platonic). \"There are only things. Space is just a relationship between things.\" — Tew\n\nWhen we say \"there's nothing in that room,\" we mean nothing *relevant to our purpose* — not a literal void. \"Nothing\" is epistemological shorthand, not a metaphysical entity.\n\nConsequence: The universe is eternal — \"its elements are uncreated and eternal\" (Peikoff). No creation ex nihilo. No annihilation into nothing.\n\n*Derives from: Existence (existence exists → nonexistence does not exist)*","x":-1656,"y":-6525,"width":695,"height":694},
		{"id":"meta-causality","type":"text","text":"## Law of Causality\n\nThe law of identity applied to action. Every entity has a specific nature — and must act in accordance with that nature. It cannot act apart from its nature (apart from its nature, a thing is nothing) or against it (A is A; contradictions are impossible).\n\n\"In any given set of circumstances, there is only one action possible to an entity, the action expressive of its identity. This is the action it will take, the action that is caused and necessitated by its nature.\" — Peikoff\n\nCrucial distinctions:\n- **Entities cause actions** — not actions causing other actions. It is not the *motion* of a billiard ball that produces effects; it is the *billiard ball* (substitute an egg — different effects).\n- **Not every entity has a cause** — the universe as a whole is eternal and uncaused (there is nothing outside totality to act as cause). What is caused is *action.*\n- **Does not require mechanical determinism** — an entity's nature determines what responses are *available* to it, not necessarily which single response must occur. This is crucial for compatibility with free will: a volitional consciousness has a specific identity that *includes* the capacity for choice.\n\n\"Every action has a cause (the cause is the nature of the entity which acts); and the same cause leads to the same effect.\" — Rand\n\nCausality is a fact independent of consciousness — not imposed by God (argument from design) nor a subjective mental form (Kant). It is inherent in being *qua* being.\n\n*Derives from: Identity + Entity (entity has a nature → must act accordingly)*","x":-3214,"y":-6525,"width":695,"height":694},
		{"id":"meta-non-contradiction","type":"text","text":"## Law of Non-Contradiction\n\nA thing cannot be A and non-A at the same time and in the same respect. \"A leaf cannot be a stone at the same time, it cannot be all red and all green at the same time, it cannot freeze and burn at the same time.\" — Rand\n\nThis is the **epistemological** tool derived from the **metaphysical** law of identity. Identity is about reality (things are what they are); non-contradiction is about thought (your identifications must not contradict each other).\n\nBecause everything is what it is, there are no contradictions *in reality.* Therefore, if your conclusions contradict each other, at least one of them fails to correspond to reality. \"Contradictions exist only in faulty identification.\"\n\nNon-contradiction makes logic possible — it is what allows step-by-step cognitive processes to track reality. Without it, \"any series of steps whatsoever would be valid, but they wouldn't correspond to reality.\" — Tew\n\nObjectivist logic involves two complementary practices:\n- **Reduction** (correspondence) — trace your abstraction back to perceptual reality\n- **Integration** (coherence) — check that it fits with everything else you know\n\nThese never conflict, because reality coheres. \"All truths cohere because reality coheres. Reality is one; truth is one.\" — Tew\n\n*Derives from: Identity (the epistemological application of A is A)*","x":-2435,"y":-6525,"width":695,"height":694},
		{"id":"meta-senses-valid","type":"text","text":"## Validity of the Senses\n\nThe validity of the senses is an axiom — a corollary of the fact of consciousness. If man is conscious of that which is, then his means of awareness *are* means of awareness, i.e., are valid. To attack the senses is to attack consciousness itself.\n\nThe senses **cannot err.** They respond automatically to stimuli via causal law — \"they have no power of choice, no power to invent, distort, or deceive.\" Error arises only at the conceptual level, in *inferences* drawn from sensory data. If a boy sees a man in a red suit and infers Santa Claus, his senses made no error — his conclusion did.\n\nA \"sensory illusion\" (stick appearing bent in water) is not a perceptual error but a testament to the senses' reliability — they faithfully report the full physical context, including how light refracts through water.\n\n**Form vs. Object:** Sensory qualities (color, sound, smell) derive from the interaction of external objects with our sense organs. They are neither purely \"in the object\" nor purely \"in the mind\" — they are **object-as-perceived.** A color-blind man and a normal-sighted man perceive the same object in different *forms* — neither is wrong, neither contradicts the other.\n\nRand: *\"The task of man's senses is to give him the evidence of existence, but the task of identifying it belongs to his reason. His senses tell him only that something is, but what it is must be learned by his mind.\"*\n\nDifferences in sensory form have no consequences for cognitive content — beings with radically different senses would reach the same scientific conclusions about reality.\n\n*Derives from: Consciousness (if you are conscious, your means of consciousness are valid)*","x":-878,"y":-6525,"width":695,"height":694},
		{"id":"meta-metaphysically-given","type":"text","text":"## The Metaphysically Given as Absolute\n\nThe culminating principle of Objectivist metaphysics: **no alternative to a fact of reality is possible or imaginable.** Every metaphysically given fact is *necessary* — necessitated by the nature of existence and therefore unchangeable by any agency.\n\nAs soon as one says of any metaphysically given fact \"it is\" — the whole Objectivist metaphysics is implicit:\n- It is what it is → **(Identity)**\n- It is lawful, inherent in the identities of entities → **(Causality)**\n- It is independent of consciousness → **(Primacy of Existence)**\n- It has to be; no alternative is possible → **(Necessity)**\n\nA fact is \"necessary\" if its nonexistence would involve a contradiction. To be is to be necessary (for metaphysically given facts). \"To be\" is \"to be something\" is \"to act accordingly\" is \"to be necessary.\"\n\n**The metaphysically given vs. the man-made:**\n- *Metaphysically given* (facts of nature): must be **accepted** — not evaluated, not praised or blamed. \"They are, were, will be, and have to be.\"\n- *Man-made* (products of choice): must be **evaluated** — accepted or rejected and changed when necessary.\n\nTwo errors from confusing them:\n1. Treating the man-made as immutable (\"you can't fight city hall\" — sanctioning any status quo)\n2. Treating the metaphysically given as alterable — the fallacy of **\"rewriting reality\"** (condemning life because pain is possible, rebelling against death, demanding non-sensory knowledge)\n\n\"Respect for reality does not guarantee success in every endeavor. But it does guarantee that, if one fails, he will not harbor a metaphysical grudge.\" — Peikoff\n\nThe rejection of this principle leads to the false mind-body dichotomy: \"my dream vs. the actual which thwarts it.\" Acceptance leads to harmony: conforming to reality is not defeat but the precondition of success.\n\n*Derives from: All axioms and corollaries integrated*","x":-3437,"y":-5420,"width":1753,"height":683,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"meta-primacy","type":"text","text":"## Primacy of Existence\n\nExistence comes first. Things are what they are **independent of consciousness** — of anyone's perceptions, images, ideas, or feelings. Consciousness is a dependent: its function is not to create or control existence, but to perceive it. \"The mind does not create the world. The mind identifies and is aware of the world.\" — Tew\n\nFrom the outset, consciousness presents itself as a faculty of perceiving an object, not of creating or changing it. A child may hate his food and refuse to look at it — but his inner state does not erase his dinner.\n\nThe opposite — **primacy of consciousness** — holds that consciousness creates reality. Three versions:\n- **Supernatural:** God's consciousness created existence (religion)\n- **Social:** A group's consciousness shapes reality (collectivism, consensus)\n- **Personal:** Each man's consciousness controls reality for him (subjectivism, Protagoras)\n\nAll are the same essential error. \"If existence exists, then it has metaphysical primacy. It is not a derivative or 'manifestation' of some true reality at its root. It *is* reality. As such, its elements are uncreated and eternal, and its laws, immutable.\" — Peikoff\n\n**Epistemological implication:** Knowledge of existence can only be gained by **extrospection** — by observing reality. No appeal to feelings, intuitions, or revelations as sources of knowledge about the world.\n\n*Derives from: Existence + Consciousness (existence is the object; consciousness is the faculty that perceives it — the object is primary)*","x":-3993,"y":-6525,"width":695,"height":694},
		{"id":"meta-mind-body","type":"text","text":"## The Mind as Action of the Body\n\nThe mind is neither independent of the body (idealism) nor reducible to specific physical matter (materialism). It is **the highest level of action involved in the maintenance of the body** — the rational, volitional aspect of the life process.\n\nTwo failed routes to life after death expose the mind's true nature:\n1. **Mind floats free of the body** — impossible, because awareness depends on the senses, which require physical sense organs. Turn them off and consciousness disappears.\n2. **Mind is tied to specific bodily matter** — impossible, because the body's matter constantly changes (eating, cell regeneration, growth) while the mind endures. Reconstructing the body from identical matter would not restore the same consciousness.\n\nThe reconciliation: mind is tied not to the body's *stuff* but to the body's *process* — the ongoing action of expending energy to acquire energy, replacing matter to maintain the form. Ship of Theseus: you are not the planks but the action of replacing the planks.\n\nBecause mind is action along a temporal continuum, **continuity is essential to identity.** Once the action stops (death), restarting biological processes creates a metaphysically new instance of action — a separate being, not you. Life is one and done.\n\n*Derives from: Consciousness (consciousness is an action, not a free-floating substance); Entity (actions have no existence apart from the entities that perform them); Causality (life is self-sustaining action)*\n*Source: Charles Tew, \"Life after Death Is Impossible\" (vjdVZBbuxMQ)*","x":-1517,"y":-5420,"width":695,"height":683},
		{"id":"meta-idealism-materialism","type":"text","text":"## Neither Idealism nor Materialism\n\nObjectivism rejects both classic metaphysical errors:\n\n**Idealism** (Plato, Augustine, Hegel): Reality is ultimately spiritual/mental — a transcendent consciousness creates or underlies existence. This is the primacy of consciousness → \"consciousness without existence.\" Leads to mysticism (\"mystics of spirit\").\n\n**Materialism** (Democritus, Hobbes, Marx, Skinner): Consciousness is a myth or useless byproduct — only physical matter is real. This is \"existence without consciousness.\" Leads to a different mysticism (\"mystics of muscle\") — rejecting the faculty of reason itself.\n\nBoth accept a false alternative invented by idealists: consciousness *vs.* science. Materialists simply pick the other side.\n\nThe **supernatural** is an assault on every axiom: a creator God violates primacy of existence; omnipotence violates identity; miracles violate causality; the \"infinite\" violates the finitude required by A is A. \"Every argument commonly offered for the notion of God leads to a contradiction of the axiomatic concepts of philosophy.\" — Peikoff\n\nThe truth: Consciousness is an attribute of certain living organisms, wholly natural, observable by introspection, with a specific nature and life-sustaining function. It is neither supernatural nor reducible to matter. \"The soul is not man's ticket to another reality; it is a development of and within nature.\" — Aristotle via Peikoff\n\nObjectivism: existence exists, *and* consciousness exists. Both are real. Neither is derivative of the other. The relationship is: existence is primary, consciousness perceives it.\n\n*Relates to: Primacy of Existence, Consciousness*","x":-711,"y":-5420,"width":695,"height":683,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"meta-entity","type":"text","text":"## Entity (Axiomatic Concept)\n\nEntities constitute the content of the world men perceive — there is nothing else to observe. An entity is a solid thing with perceivable shape (rock, person, table). By extension: solar systems, corporations, subatomic particles — all reducible to combinations or aspects of entities in the primary sense.\n\nAll other categories of being — qualities, quantities, relationships, actions — are merely *aspects of entities.* There is no \"red\" apart from the thing that is red. No \"walking\" apart from the creature that walks. **There are no floating actions; there are only actions performed by entities.**\n\nThe child grasps \"entity\" before \"identity\" — he must first perceive that objects exist (integrating sensations into percepts of things) before he can distinguish *this* object from *that.*\n\nEntity + Identity → the foundation for grasping Causality.\n\n**Status:** Axiomatic concept (presupposed by all subsequent cognition, but not itself a basic axiom)\n**Key principle:** \"Action\" is the name for what entities do — actions have no existence apart from the entities that perform them","x":-3000,"y":-7290,"width":695,"height":527},
		{"id":"meta-volition","type":"text","text":"## Volition (Free Will)\n\nVolition is an **irreducible metaphysical fact** — a corollary of the axiom of consciousness. Not every consciousness has free will, but every *fallible, conceptual* consciousness must. An organism that can err in its identifications must have the power to initiate or suspend the cognitive process; otherwise error has no meaning. This is a fact about the **nature of reality**, not merely about how man happens to think. Volition belongs to the same metaphysical stratum as causality, identity, and entity.\n\n**Validation is introspective, not rationalistic.** The self-refuting argument against determinism is a useful corollary, but it is not the *proof*. The proof is that you can look inward and *see* yourself choosing — direct, firsthand observation of your own freedom of choice. Free will is as directly observable as any other existent.\n\n**Compatibility with causality.** The law of causality says entities act according to their nature. It does not require that all action be mechanistic. Definite does not mean linear, and identity is not linearity. Man's nature *includes* the capacity for choice. Causality describes the *form* of action (entity-driven); volition is a *type* of entity-driven action.\n\n**Determinism is self-refuting.** If all ideas are necessitated by prior physical causes, the determinist cannot claim his conclusion is *true* — he had no choice but to reach it, rational or not. But note: this argument is a *consequence* of free will's existence, not its proof.\n\nRand: **\"The faculty of reason IS the faculty of volition.\"** This removes free will from mysticism (Kant's noumenal freedom, Libertarian miracle-agency) and grounds it in man's this-worldly, natural identity. Free will is not a violation of natural law but an *expression* of it — the way a rational entity acts.\n\n*Derives from: Consciousness (corollary — a fallible conceptual consciousness must be volitional)*\n*Compatible with: Causality (entity acts according to its nature; man's nature includes choice)*\n*Epistemological application: see Epistemology → \"Volition: The Epistemological Locus\"*","x":-80,"y":-6573,"width":695,"height":789,"color":"2"}
	],
